# 2. `cd` Command

## What is `cd`?

`cd` means **change directory**.

It is used to move from one directory to another.

Think of a school building:

```text
School
‚Ēú‚ĒÄ‚ĒÄ Classroom
‚Ēú‚ĒÄ‚ĒÄ Library
‚Ēú‚ĒÄ‚ĒÄ Computer Lab
‚ĒĒ‚ĒÄ‚ĒÄ Playground
```

Walking from the classroom to the library is similar to changing directories.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
cd [DIRECTORY]
```

---

## Go to a Directory

```bash
cd Documents
```

---

## Use an Absolute Path

```bash
cd /var/log
```

An absolute path starts from `/`.

---

## Use a Relative Path

Suppose you are in:

```text
/home/student
```

and `Documents` exists inside it.

Use:

```bash
cd Documents
```

---

## `cd ..` ‚Äď Move One Level Up

```bash
cd ..
```

Example:

Before:

```text
/home/student/Documents
```

After:

```text
/home/student
```

---

## `cd ../..` ‚Äď Move Two Levels Up

```bash
cd ../..
```

Example:

Before:

```text
/home/student/project/logs
```

After:

```text
/home/student
```

---

## `cd ~` ‚Äď Go to Home Directory

```bash
cd ~
```

You can also usually use:

```bash
cd
```

Both take you to the current user's home directory.

---

## `cd -` ‚Äď Go to Previous Directory

Suppose you move from:

```text
/home/student
```

to:

```text
/var/log
```

Now run:

```bash
cd -
```

You return to the previous directory.

This is useful when switching between two locations.

---

## `cd .` ‚Äď Stay in Current Directory

```bash
cd .
```

`.` means the current directory.

The command does not move you anywhere.

---

## Important Note About `cd`

`cd` is normally a shell built-in command, not a regular external program.

You can check using:

```bash
type cd
```

Example output:

```text
cd is a shell builtin
```

Because of this, `cd` does not use normal short options like many external Linux commands.

For help in Bash:

```bash
help cd
```

---

## Useful `cd` Commands

```bash
cd /var/log
cd ..
cd ../..
cd ~
cd
cd -
```

---

## PSA Scenario ‚Äď Navigate to Application Logs

```bash
cd /app/logs
pwd
ls -ltr
```

`pwd` confirms your current location before you inspect or modify anything.

