# 4. `rmdir` Command

## What is `rmdir`?

`rmdir` means **remove directory**.

It removes **empty directories only**.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
rmdir [OPTIONS] DIRECTORY_NAME
```

---

## Remove an Empty Directory

```bash
mkdir test
rmdir test
```

This works because `test` is empty.

---

## What Happens if the Directory Contains Files?

Suppose:

```text
logs/
‚ĒĒ‚ĒÄ‚ĒÄ app.log
```

Run:

```bash
rmdir logs
```

You will get an error similar to:

```text
rmdir: failed to remove 'logs': Directory not empty
```

This safety behavior is important.

---

## Remove Multiple Empty Directories

```bash
rmdir dir1 dir2 dir3
```

All specified directories must be empty to be removed successfully.

---

## `rmdir -p` ‚Äď Remove Directory and Empty Parents

Create:

```bash
mkdir -p project/logs/archive
```

Then:

```bash
rmdir -p project/logs/archive
```

If each directory becomes empty, it removes:

```text
archive
logs
project
```

---

## `rmdir -v` ‚Äď Verbose Mode

On systems where GNU `rmdir` is used:

```bash
rmdir -v test
```

It displays information about the directory being removed.

---

## Important Difference

```text
rmdir directory
```

removes only an empty directory.

```text
rm -r directory
```

removes a directory and its contents recursively.

Do not treat them as interchangeable.

